FILE: /bodies/Raytheon_FENCE.body

WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified body profile for the Raytheon event-based mid-wave infrared
(MWIR) camera developed under DARPA's Fast Event-based Neuromorphic Camera
and Electronics (FENCE) program. It defines the event-based sensing model,
the neuromorphic readout architecture, the pixel-level motion detection
formula, and the spectral sensitivity range (3–5 μm MWIR).

WHY IT EXISTS
Traditional infrared cameras generate enormous data rates (Gbps) by
streaming full frames at high speed. The FENCE camera transmits only
pixel-level changes (events), reducing bandwidth and power by orders of
magnitude. This enables real-time tracking of high-speed targets with
minimal processing. GIOP includes this as the first neuromorphic sensor
profile in its Bodies catalogue.

HOW IT WORKS
1. Event Generation Model:
   A pixel (x,y) generates an event at time t if:
     |log(I(x,y,t)) - log(I(x,y,t_last))| > threshold
   where I is the incident irradiance, threshold is the contrast
   sensitivity (typically 15-20% for MWIR).

2. Event Format:
   Each event is a tuple: (x, y, t, polarity)
   polarity = +1 (ON event, intensity increase)
   polarity = -1 (OFF event, intensity decrease)
   Temporal resolution: microsecond (event timestamp).

3. Bandwidth Reduction:
   Conventional MWIR: 640×512 @ 1000 fps, 16-bit = ~5.2 Gbps.
   FENCE camera: events/second depend on scene motion. For typical
   tracking scenarios, data rate is 10-100 Mbps (50-500× reduction).

4. Spectral Sensitivity:
   Wavelength range: 3 μm – 5 μm (MWIR, thermal imaging).
   Detects thermal emissions from engines, exhausts, and other heat
   sources.

5. Reconstruction:
   To produce conventional frames, events are accumulated over a time
   window Δt and rendered as an intensity image:
     I_accum(x,y) = Σ events(x,y) * polarity
   Alternatively, neural reconstruction (E2VID) can produce high-
   quality video from event streams.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Military target tracking and missile defence
- Industrial monitoring (high-speed machinery)
- GIOP event-based imaging pipelines.

WHO USES IT
L1 Architects defining neuromorphic sensor profiles; L2 Engineers
building event-to-video reconstruction pipelines.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Introduces event-based neuromorphic sensing to GIOP, enabling ultra-
low-bandwidth, high-speed MWIR imaging for applications where
conventional frame-based cameras are infeasible.

